snippet.textDisplay:
Take a bow! 

What joy, it's to listen Abida. 

Someone, today, saw my tonsured head and said "tum to Sufi ho gaye" I thought to myself sufism has more to do with striped heart much less with striped head. 

Listen to her and you'll know what I mean.

"Kardega tu
Jo ik nazar
Saare gunaah jayengege dhul

Maula-e-kull
Aaa..
Maula e kul

Main bekhabar tu baakhabar

Jalwa tera noor-e-sahar

Kardega tu
Jo ik nazar

Band raaste jayengege khul
Maula e kul

Berang mein har rang tu
Teri mujhe hai justjoo

Kardega tu
Jo ik nazar

Rang ishq ke jayenge ghul
Maula-e-kull"

snippet.textDisplay: The Five Purified Personages (the Punj Tan Paak) symbolize the masculine Jalali (Muhammad, Ali, Hussain) and feminine Jamali (Lady Fatima, Hassan) characteristics of God who is without gender or equal in His Essence. We know what God is from how these personages manifest His characteristics in time and space. When Abida Perveen sings with such abandon about "maula", her voice shows her eternal quest for the Face of God who according to one hadith reflects in the faces of Muhammad and Ali. A look at the faces of these personages shows us the purity of God's Essence. When she sings with great pain about the daughter of the Holy Prophet, she manifests man's quest for the Pure Feminine which is hidden from the material world--how it suffers in the world against the masculine/yang forces, yet how strong this feminine/yin Force is as it underlies and supports all the actions of the masculine/yang forces. She is the reason for the strength of masculine force of Muhammad and Ali. Of course the masculine and feminine forces will be balanced in a state called Paradise whose Masters are Fatima, Hassan and Hussain while the waters of God's Mercy flow from the 'hands'of Prophet Muhammad and God's Justice flows from the 'sword' of Ali.
